item.title: Mexico's Economy Shrinks in First Quarter on Early Pandemic Effects
item.description: Mexico’s economy contracted 1.2% in the first quarter of the year, as the coronavirus pandemic started to affect industry and services. The decline was smaller than the preliminary 1.6% contraction reported at the end of April.

item.title: Amid U.S. Pressure, Israel Rejects Chinese Bid for Major Infrastructure Project
item.description: Israel awarded the contract for what is slated to be the world’s largest desalination plant to a local company, a move that prevents the country from getting entangled in the escalating tensions between the U.S. and China.

item.title: Coronavirus Further Strains a U.K. Union Already Under Pressure
item.description: England, Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland, still reeling from Brexit, go their separate ways in trying to manage the pandemic.

item.title: How Hong Kong, Singapore Kept Virus Death Rates Low
item.description: Hong Kong and Singapore’s coronavirus fatality rates are among the lowest in the world, showing that outbreaks don’t have to result in large-scale loss of life. Their playbook: test widely, quarantine aggressively and treat patients early.

item.title: Western Economies See Biggest Slump Since Financial Crisis
item.description: The world’s developed economies saw the largest fall in output since the global financial crisis in the first three months of the year, as governments began to impose lockdowns designed to limit the spread of the novel coronavirus.

item.title: Europe Is Subsidizing Millions of Paychecks. Companies Want to Keep It That Way, for Now.
item.description: Europe’s strategy of placing tens of millions of workers on paid leave has so far succeeded in stemming the widespread unemployment that has been seen in the U.S., but now governments across the continent are grappling with how to wean companies and workers off the support.
